Usage Instructions
1.	Download the UCI Heart Disease dataset and convert it into MATLAB matrices named:
cleveland, Hungarian, switzerland, VA
along with their corresponding class vectors.
2.	Place the dataset file (data.mat) in the MATLAB working directory.
3.	Ensure all required helper functions are available in the MATLAB path.
4.	Execute the main script:
clear; clc; close all;
load data
5.	Run the script sequentially to reproduce clustering, visualization, and evaluation outputs.

Requirements
The implementation was developed and tested using:
•	Software Environment: MATLAB R2021b
•	Operating System: Windows 10 (64-bit)
Required MATLAB toolboxes:
•	Statistics and Machine Learning Toolbox – for distance computations, statistical operations, and classifier comparisons.
•	MATLAB Base Functions – for matrix manipulation, plotting, and numerical processing.
The DBSCAN function is implemented as a user-defined routine and does not require additional proprietary libraries beyond standard MATLAB functionality.

Methodology
The anomaly detection framework follows a structured sequence of processing stages:
1. Data Preparation
Clinical observations from multiple repositories are merged into a single dataset. Invalid entries and missing values are normalized through constant substitution to preserve computational stability.
2. Feature Selection
A filter-based strategy ranks features using statistical dispersion characteristics. Attributes exhibiting higher variability are prioritized to enhance cluster separability and reduce dimensional redundancy.
3. Density-Based Clustering
The DBSCAN algorithm is employed to discover clusters based on local density structures. Unlike centroid-based approaches, DBSCAN avoids assumptions regarding cluster count or initialization, making it robust to noise and irregular cluster geometries.
4. Adaptive Parameter Estimation
The neighborhood radius (ε) and minimum neighbor count (MinPts) are determined dynamically using dataset-dependent heuristics. This adaptive mechanism mitigates sensitivity associated with fixed parameter selection.
5. Anomaly Identification
Samples not belonging to any dense region are labeled as anomalies. In the clinical interpretation, these instances correspond to potential heart disease cases.
6. Comparative Classification
To contextualize the proposed model’s performance, predictions are compared with several supervised classifiers, including KNN, SVM, Neural Networks, Decision Trees, and Naïve Bayes.

Assessment Metrics
Performance evaluation is conducted using metrics commonly adopted in medical decision-support systems:
•	Accuracy – Quantifies overall prediction correctness.
•	Recall (Sensitivity) – Measures the ability to identify anomalous (patient) instances.
•	Precision – Evaluates reliability of anomaly predictions.
•	F-measure – Balances precision and recall, particularly relevant under class imbalance.
•	True Positive Rate / True Negative Rate – Provide complementary insight into diagnostic reliability.
These metrics are selected to ensure clinically meaningful interpretation of model behavior, where both missed detections and false alarms carry significant implications.

Materials & Methods – Computing Infrastructure
All simulations were performed under the following configuration:
•	Hardware: Laptop ASUS N56J – Intel Core i7 Processor, 8 GB RAM
•	Operating System: Windows 10 (64-bit)
•	Software: MATLAB R2021b
No distributed or high-performance computing resources were required.

