This implementation corresponds to the methodology presented in:
Nanehkaran, Y., Zhu Licai, Chen, J., Jamel, A. A. M., Shengnan, Z., Navaei, Y. D., & Abdollahzadeh Aghbolagh, M. (2022).
Citation
Anomaly Detection in Heart Disease Using a Density‐Based Unsupervised Approach.
Wireless Communications and Mobile Computing, 2022(1), 6913043.
DOI: 10.1155/2022/6913043

Summary of the Published Study
The associated study introduces an adaptive density-based unsupervised framework for detecting anomalies in heart disease datasets. The proposed model combines filter-based feature selection with DBSCAN clustering, addressing inherent limitations of partition-based clustering methods, particularly sensitivity to noise and dependence on predefined cluster counts. A central contribution of the work lies in the adaptive estimation of DBSCAN parameters, enabling near-optimal clustering performance without manual tuning. Experimental analysis demonstrates that the density-driven strategy effectively distinguishes normal and abnormal instances, achieving approximately 95% prediction accuracy and outperforming several conventional classification techniques.

Conclusions
The density-based unsupervised paradigm provides a robust mechanism for anomaly detection in medical datasets characterized by noise, heterogeneity, and partially redundant features. Adaptive parameter selection enhances clustering stability and diagnostic reliability. The results support the viability of unsupervised learning as a complementary tool for clinical decision-support systems.

Limitations
Several limitations warrant consideration:
•	Constant imputation may influence feature distributions
•	Parameter heuristics remain dataset-dependent
•	Clinical datasets may exhibit varying noise characteristics
•	Unsupervised labeling does not replace expert diagnosis
•	Generalization requires validation across broader populations
Future work may explore advanced imputation strategies, automated parameter optimization, and hybrid semi-supervised extensions.

